  "We use alternative means to achieve the same effect": [
   {
    "text": "In English, we do not use “binyan” to produce families of related verbs. ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "topLevelNodes": [
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "Rather, in English you have one simple verb like “eat,” and then you add other words to form larger ideas like “he made someone eat,” or “he was eaten,” etc, whereas in Hebrew and Aramaic those permutations are baked into the verb itself.",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "Additionally, in English, words like “buy” and “sell” have no visual similarity, whereas in Hebrew and Aramaic, “to buy” (לִקְנוֹת) and “to sell” (לְהִיקָּנוֹת) would be “two binyans” of the same shoresh (קנה), and would share many of the same letters.",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     }
    ],
    "type": "outline"
   }
